1. Introduction 
In modern manufacturing, preserving the quality and reliability of products is of primary 
importance. Defect detection plays a grave role in this process, helping as a fundamental step 
in retaining product standards, minimizing waste, and enhancing overall efficiency. The rise 
of automation and advanced imaging techniques has transformed how manufacturers identify 
and address defects, switching from manual inspections to more sophisticated, automated 
systems. These systems not only enhance the accuracy and speed of defect detection but also 
help in preserving consistent quality across large-scale production [1]. 
In industries such as automotive manufacturing, where precision and safety are non
negotiable, the prominence of defect detection is even more vibrant. Components such as 
battery lids, which are decisive to the functionality and safety of electric vehicles, require 
demanding inspection to ensure that they meet high standards. A defect in such a critical 
component could lead to substantial operational failures or safety hazards, creating reliable 
detection systems essential [2]. 
Current progress in deep learning, especially with Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), has 
made it much easier to automatically detect defects [3]. CNNs, with their ability to learn 
hierarchical representations of visual data, have been broadly adopted in image classification 
and object detection tasks [3]. Among the various CNN architectures, VGG16 has arose as a 
powerful model due to its deep architecture and solid feature extraction capabilities [4]. 
VGG16's ability to capture fine details in images makes it primarily appropriate for detecting 
subtle defects in manufacturing components. 
This study focuses around the application of CNNs, specifically the VGG16 architecture, for 
detecting defects in Volvo's battery lids. By leveraging VGG16, the research aims to develop an 
automated system capable of identifying defects such as cracks, uneven seals, and seal overflow 
with high level accuracy. The implementation of these technologies in the manufacturing 
process not only assures to augment the quality control mechanisms at Volvo but also 
characterises a significant advancement in the broader field of automated defect detection. 
The scope of this study includes the development, implementation, and evaluation of a defect 
detection system personalised for Volvo's specific needs. This contains the collection and pre
processing of image data, the design and training of the VGG16 model, and the integration of 
the model into a practical system for real-time defect detection. The uniqueness and 
significance of this research lies in its potential to improve the reliability of battery lids, thereby 
contributing to the safety and performance of Volvo's electric vehicles. 
