In the perspective of industrial manufacturing, mainly in the sealing processes used in the 
automotive industry, ensuring consistent and reliable quality is supreme for both product 
safety and performance. Traditional methods for detecting defects, such as manual inspection 
and rule-based systems, have substantial drawbacks. Manual inspection, which trusts heavily 
on human operators, is basically subjective, labour-intensive, and time-consuming. This 
c21binba 
subjectivity can lead to inconsistencies, and in case of high-volume manufacturing 
environments, even minor defects or irregularities can be easily missed during visual 
inspections [5]. 
Rule-based systems, even though offering a more structured approach than manual inspection, 
frequently fail to adapt to variations in the sealing process or changing environmental 
conditions. These systems can struggle to effectively handle the dynamic nature of 
manufacturing processes, where factors such as material variations, machine wear, and 
environmental impacts can lead to defects that do not follow to predefined rules [6]. 
This project pursues to address these limitations by developing an automated defect detection 
system specifically custom-made to the battery lid sealing processes at Volvo Cars. By 
leveraging advancements in computer vision and machine learning, especially Convolutional 
Neural Networks (CNNs) and the VGG16 architecture, the proposed system aims to analyse 
images and video footage in real-time to detect and classify defects such as cracks, uneven 
surfaces, and seal overflows [3]. The integration of these technologies aptitudes to expressively 
improve the accuracy and efficiency of the defect detection process, eventually improving the 
overall quality control in the manufacturing line. 
Importance of a Balanced Dataset 
The dataset used in this project is meticulously balanced, with 400 images per defect class. 
This balance is crucial for several reasons: 
●    Equal Representation: A balanced dataset confirms that the model does not become 
biased towards any particular defect type, which is critical for accomplishing consistent 
and reliable performance across all classes. 
●    Model Generalization: With equal representation of each defect class, the model can 
accurately detect and classify all types of defects in various scenarios without favouring 
one class over another. 
Key Challenges 
1. Environmental Variability: The sealing process is subject to changes in the 
manufacturing environment, such as variable lighting conditions, which can affect the 
intensity of shadows on the sealing portion. These fluctuations can obscure defects and 
must be accounted for in the system’s design. 
2. Background Noise: The live camera setup may accidentally capture additional objects 
in the background, introducing noise that can disturb with defect detection. Robust 
image pre-processing techniques are necessary to isolate the battery lid sealing from 
irrelevant background details. 
3. Obstruction Issues: At times, the sealing application machinery may hinder the view of 
the battery lid, resulting in images that are not suitable for analysis. These obstructed 
images need to be identified and excluded from the dataset to prevent inaccurate model 
training. 
4. Lack of Defect Data: There is a limited availability of images portraying actual defects, 
which poses a challenge for training the machine learning models. The project involves 
manually extracting and labelling images from video files to create a comprehensive 
dataset for training. 
