Research Objectives 
The primary objective of this thesis project is to design and implement a full-fledged functional 
system for the detection and classification of defects in Volvo Cars' battery lids. The project is 
mainly focused on accomplishing the following goals: 
●  Develop a Comprehensive Dataset: Create a dataset of images that captures a wide 
range of defects in battery lids, containing cracks, uneven seals and seal overflows. This 
dataset will act as the main basis for training and testing the defect detection models. 
●    Apply Advanced Computer Vision and Machine Learning Techniques: Application of 
advanced techniques in computer vision and deep learning to extract relevant features 
from the images. This contains experimenting with various models and approaches to 
successfully train models that can accurately detect and classify defects. 
●    Evaluate Model Performance: The performance of the developed system is evaluated 
using metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score. Based on the evaluation, 
refine and optimize the models to achieve the highest possible detection accuracy. 
●    Validate in Real-World Settings: Implement the developed system in a real-world 
production environment at Volvo Cars. The system will be tested for its capacity to 
precisely identify defects in battery lids during the manufacturing process, confirming 
that it meets industrial standards and operational requirements. 
1.3    
