2. Background 
This chapter highlights an in-depth overview to the field of automated defect detection in 
manufacturing, with a specific focus on detecting defects in Betaguard Yellow sealing used in 
the battery lids of Volvo Cars. A deep understanding of the vital role that defect detection plays 
in retaining the safety and reliability of electric vehicle components is essential to grasp the 
importance of this research. This chapter also covers the limitations of traditional manual 
inspection methods and the growing possibilities of machine learning and computer vision 
technologies to enhance the efficiency and accuracy of quality control in the automotive 
industry. 
2.1 Preliminaries 
This section provides a foundational overview of the key concepts and techniques necessary 
for understanding automated defect detection, particularly in the context of Betaguard Yellow 
sealing in Volvo Cars' battery lids. These foundational elements are crucial for the development 
and application of advanced machine learning models in this study. 
2.1.1 Image Pre-processing Techniques  
Before analysing images for defects or features, pre-processing is crucial. This step ensures 
that images are cleaned and standardized, making them suitable for analysis. Here are the key 
pre-processing techniques: 
Video to Frame Conversion 
Extracting frames from a video at regular intervals, such as one frame per second, enables 
detailed inspection of each frame. This technique is particularly useful for detecting defects 
that may only appear briefly, allowing for more accurate analysis by examining each frame 
individually rather than processing continuous video data [9]. 
Image Resizing 
Standardizing the resolution of images to a constant size, such as 320x320 pixels, guarantees 
consistency across the dataset. This resizing step is crucial for maintaining the balance between 
image details and processing efficiency, facilitating effective and reliable performance of 
machine learning models [9]. 
Noise Reduction 
 Gaussian Blur: Applies a smoothing filter to reduce image noise and detail by 
averaging pixel values in a neighbourhood. This helps in reducing the impact of random 
variations and makes the subsequent feature extraction more robust [9] [10]. 
 Median Filtering: Replaces each pixel's value with the median of its neighbouring 
pixels. This technique is particularly effective at removing speckle noise while 
preserving edges, which is important for clear defect detection [9] [10]. 
Image Normalization 
10 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
Adjusting pixel intensity values to a standardized range (e.g., 0(black) to 255(white)) helps in 
mitigating the effects of varying lighting conditions across images. This normalization process 
ensures that models can focus on relevant features rather than being skewed by differences in 
brightness and contrast [9]. 
2.1.2   Feature extraction 
Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) 
Color-based segmentation segregates specific color ranges from an image, effectually 
distinguishing the object of interest from the background. By converting images to a color 
space that emphasizes distinct colors, this technique enables precise segmentation of relevant 
areas. This method is crucial for focusing analysis on specific features or regions in an image 
while filtering out irrelevant background elements [26]. 
Image Thresholding 
Thresholding simplifies images by converting them into binary format, where each pixel is 
either black or white. This technique is essential for isolating objects from the background. 
 Binary Thresholding: In binary thresholding, pixel intensities are compared against 
a predefined threshold value. Pixels above the threshold are turned white, representing 
the object, while those below are turned black, indicating the background. This 
approach mainly focuses on the object of interest and enables defect detection by 
clearly separating it from the background [10]. 
 Adaptive Thresholding: When an image has changing lighting conditions, adaptive 
thresholding computes different thresholds for smaller regions of the image. This 
method adjusts to local lighting variations, ensuring accurate separation of objects 
from the background despite uneven lighting [11]. 
Edge Detection Techniques 
Edge detection is very much important for identifying object boundaries in an image, which is 
necessary for detecting defects. 
 Sobel Edge Detection: The Sobel method uses convolutional filters to estimate 
gradients in pixel intensities, emphasizing areas with sharp intensity changes. While 
effective for basic edge detection, it may overlook finer details. It is often used as an 
initial step due to its simplicity and efficiency [11]. 
 Canny Edge Detection: Canny edge detection offers high precision by using a multi
step process: smoothing the image with a Gaussian filter to reduce noise, finding 
gradient intensities to identify potential edges, applying non-maximum suppression to 
thin edges, and using edge tracking by hysteresis to finalize detection. This method is 
particularly adept at identifying subtle or minor defects [11]. 
11 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
Image Alignment and Contour-Based Defect Detection 
Accurate image alignment and contour analysis also acts as important factors for effective 
defect detection. 
 Image Alignment: This process adjusts images taken from various angles or 
positions to make sure they are properly oriented for comparison. Proper alignment is 
important for detecting subtle defects that might be masked by misalignment [12]. 
 Contour-Based Defect Detection: Contour detection recognizes the outlines of 
objects in an image. Investigating these contours helps in spotting irregularities that 
may indicate defects. Deviations from expected shapes or smooth contours can signify 
potential issues, making contour analysis an effective method for detecting structural 
defects [12]. 
2.1.3   Deep learning 
Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) 
Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), also known as ConvNets, are a type of deep neural 
network architecture inspired by the organisation of the animal visual cortex, mainly the 
receptive fields of neurons. CNNs are obviously aimed to process data with a grid-like topology, 
such as images, creating them highly suggested for tasks in computer vision [19]. 
Key components of CNNs include: 
1.    Convolutional Layers: These layers apply a set of learnable filters (also called kernels) to 
input data, making convolution operations. Each filter abstracts specific features from the 
input image by sliding across it and computing dot products with the input at both position. 
Convolutional layers are largely liable for learning hierarchical representations of features, 
such as edges, textures, and object parts. 
2.    Pooling Layers: These layers reduce the size of the feature maps created by convolutional 
layers, keeping the most important information. Two common types of pooling are max 
pooling, which keeps the highest value in each region, and average pooling, which keeps 
the average value. These layers help make the network less sensitive to small changes in 
the input and reduce the amount of processing needed [19]. 
3.  Activation Functions: Activation functions deploys non-linearity into the network, letting it 
to learn complex patterns and relationships in the data. The most common activation 
functions that are used in CNNs include ReLU (Rectified Linear Unit), sigmoid, and tanh. 
ReLU is mostly chosen for to its simplicity and effectiveness in mitigating the vanishing 
gradient problem. 
4.     Fully Connected Layers: Fully connected layers, also known as dense layers, connect every 
neuron in one layer to every neuron in the subsequent layer. These layers execute high
level reasoning and decision-making based on the features learned by the convolutional 
and pooling layers. Fully connected layers are typically found at the end of the CNN 
12 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
architecture and are commonly followed by a softmax activation function for classification 
jobs. 
CNNs have done very well in different computer vision tasks like image classification, object 
detection, and semantic segmentation [19]. Hence itself they have been applied in diverse 
domains such as healthcare, autonomous vehicles, robotics, and natural language processing 
(NLP) [20]. 
VGG16 
VGG16 is a convolutional neural network (CNN) architecture proposed by Karen Simonyan 
and Andrew Zisserman from the Visual Geometry Group (VGG) at the University of Oxford. It 
is characterised by its deep architecture comprising 16 convolutional layers, hence the name 
"VGG16" [18]. 
Key features of the VGG16 architecture include: 
Deep Convolutional Layers: VGG16 consists of multiple convolutional layers, each trailed by a 
rectified linear unit (ReLU) activation function and a max-pooling layer. This design enables 
the network to learn hierarchical features from raw image data. 
Uniform Structure: The architecture keeps a consistent pattern throughout, with 3x3 
convolutional filters and 2x2 max-pooling layers. 
Large Number of Parameters: Due to its depth and number of parameters, VGG16 has a high 
capacity for learning intricate features from images. Also, this also makes it computationally 
expensive and memory-intensive. 
Pre-training on ImageNet: VGG16 was firstly trained on the large-scale ImageNet dataset for 
image classification tasks. This pre-training process allows the model to capture generic 
features from a wide range of images, making it appropriate for transfer learning to various 
other tasks, including defect detection. 
Overall, VGG16 is renowned for its simplicity and effectiveness in image recognition tasks. 
Despite its relatively large number of parameters, it has been widely adopted in both research 
and practical applications due to its distinguished performance [18]. 
2.2   Research Background 
In this section, explore the relevant research conducted in the field of defect detection within 
manufacturing, with an emphasis on the techniques and methodologies employed to address 
challenges to those in this study. The research background mainly contains studies on image 
processing techniques and the application of machine learning for defect detection, providing 
an understanding of the approaches and strategies that have been already developed and 
exploited in these domains. 
2.2.1   Defect Detection in Manufacturing 
Traditionally, Defect Detection has been performed through manual inspection, a method 
known for its thoroughness but also for being labour-intensive and prone to human error. In 
13 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
high-volume production environments, the consistency and precision required to maintain 
high standards are often lacking in manual approaches, leading to prospective oversights in 
quality assurance. However, advancements in automation and digital imaging have 
familiarised more reliable and efficient systems, considerably improving the quality control 
process in manufacturing [5]. 
Zhou et al. [6] discuss the application of automated defect detection systems using image 
processing techniques. Their research highlights the major advantages of automation over 
manual inspection, including increased accuracy and reduced inspection time. By employing 
advanced image processing methods, the study establishes how defects can be identified more 
precisely, thus reducing the chances of human error. This study is particularly pertinent to the 
current project, as it underscores the prominence of automation in defect detection and 
provides foundational techniques that can be adapted for detecting defects in battery lids. [6]. 
Chen et al. [7] provide an inclusive review of various defect detection methods in 
manufacturing, grouping them into traditional and advanced techniques. The study elucidates 
a significant shift towards machine learning and deep learning approaches, which offer 
superior accuracy and efficiency, essential for upholding high standards in manufacturing 
quality control. This review aligns with the project objectives, highlighting the emphasis of 
machine learning to revolutionize defect detection processes, making it a critical reference for 
developing our automated system for battery lid inspection [7]. 
2.2.2   Image Processing Techniques 
The detection and analysis of defects in manufacturing processes depend heavily on image 
processing. It uses a number of pre-processing approaches to emphasize and identify potential 
defects in images more easily. Contour analysis, thresholding, and edge detection are 
important methods that provide distinct benefits for detecting different kinds of defects. 
Cruzada [8] explains that the HSV (Hue, Saturation, Value) colour space approach works very 
well for image segmentation. HSV is more useful for applications where colour distinction is 
important since it distinguishes colour information from intensity, in contrast to the RGB 
colour space. 
Edge detection methods, such as the Canny and Sobel filters, are mostly used to detect edges 
in images. These techniques help identify cracks and other discontinuities by highlighting 
significant changes in pixel intensity. Haidar [9] extensively discusses these methods, 
explaining how edge detection can effectively locate defects that are not easily visible to the 
naked eye. This is critical for the current project, where detecting subtle defects like cracks and 
uneven seals is essential 
Another crucial method is binary thresholding, which divides a grayscale image into two parts 
according to a predetermined threshold value. More precise fault detection is made possible 
by this technology, which is especially helpful in differentiating the sealing sections from the 
remainder of the battery lid [10]. 
Finding anomalies like uneven seals requires the use of contour analysis, which is the process 
of identifying and evaluating an object's shape in an image. The contour extraction and analysis 
techniques described by Chen et al. [12] are crucial for locating shape-based defects. By 
14 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
precisely identifying and analysing the areas of interest on the battery lid, contour analysis 
improves the precision of our defect detection method. 
Image processing techniques play a crucial role in preparing battery lid images for automated 
defect detection using machine learning. By applying techniques like grayscale conversion, 
edge detection, filtering, morphological operations, segmentation, and contour analysis, a 
robust system can be developed to identify cracks, uneven seals, and improper seals in Volvo 
Cars' battery lids with Betaguard Yellow sealing material. 
2.2.3   Machine Learning for Defect Detection 
Machine learning, specifically deep learning, brought about a key revolution in defect detection 
by enabling automated, high-accuracy identification and classification of defects. 
Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) are mainly effective for tasks involving image 
recognition and analysis, making them perfect for detecting and classifying defects in 
manufacturing [16]. 
In their paper, Huang and Zhu [14] feature an advanced defect detection system for automotive 
parts using the YOLO V7 (You Only Look Once version 7) object detection algorithm. YOLO V7 
is well known for its real-time detection capabilities and high accuracy. The authors tailored 
YOLO V7 to the specific challenges of automotive parts inspection by including a custom 
dataset of annotated defects and applying transfer learning to power up the pre-trained 
models. The method contains pre-processing images to enhance defect visibility, feeding them 
into the YOLO V7network, and using the algorithm's ability to predict bounding boxes and 
class probabilities to identify and localise defects. Their results indicate that YOLO V7 can 
remarkably detect a variety of defects with high precision and speed, making it a perfect choice 
for integration into automated inspection systems in automotive manufacturing [14]. 
In their comprehensive review, Saberironaghi, Ren, and El-Gindy [13] discuss various deep 
learning techniques for defect detection in industrial products, with an extra focus on 
Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs). The authors highlight that CNNs are highly effective 
for image-based defect detection due to their ability to automatically learn and extract 
hierarchical features from raw image data. The paper explains the different CNN architectures 
and their applications, underscoring that deeper networks like ResNet and DenseNet that have 
shown superior performance in complex defect detection tasks due to their ability to capture 
more abstract features and manage vanishing gradient problems. The review also covers the 
integration of CNNs with other deep learning models, such as Generative Adversarial Networks 
(GANs) for data augmentation and transfer learning, to increase the detection accuracy and 
robustness of defect detection systems in several industrial applications [13]. 
In the research article "Circuit Manufacturing Defect Detection Using VGG16 Convolutional 
Neural Networks" by Sara A. Althubiti et al. [15], the authors employ the VGG16 model to 
detect and classify defects in printed circuit boards (PCBs). The methodology involves pre
processing PCB images by converting them to grayscale and normalising pixel values to 
enhance consistency and quality. Key steps include extracting regions of interest (RoI) to focus 
on defect-prone areas, applying data augmentation techniques like rotation and scaling to 
improve model robustness, and using transfer learning with the pre-trained VGG16 model. The 
model's convolutional layers extract hierarchical features from the images, which are then 
classified through fully connected layers to identify defects such as false copper, mouse bites, 
15 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
missing holes, and open circuits. This approach demonstrates VGG16's effectiveness in 
enhancing the accuracy and efficiency of automated defect detection in circuit manufacturing 
[15]. 
The above-reviewed studies and techniques are integral to the development of our automated 
defect detection system for battery lid sealing processes at Volvo Cars. The insights from Zho 
et al. [5] and Chen et al. [7] provide a strong justification for the shift towards automated and 
machine learning-based defect detection methods, which form the core of our project. Image 
processing techniques such as edge detection, thresholding, and contour analysis are critical 
for pre-processing and feature extraction, directly supporting our methodology. Also, the 
advancements in machine learning, particularly the use of CNNs as demonstrated by 
Saberironaghi, Ren, and El-Gindy [13], Sara A. Althubiti et al. [15], and Huang and Zhu [14], 
underscore the potential of these techniques to significantly enhance defect detection accuracy 
and efficiency. These studies collectively offer a strong foundation for our project, guiding the 
development of a sophisticated and reliable defect detection system for battery lids. 
