3. Method 
The methodology outlined in this section provides a systematic method for detecting defects 
in Betaguard sealing, which is a critical part of Volvo Cars' battery lids. By succeeding a 
structured framework that includes data acquisition, pre-processing, feature extraction, model 
development, and validation, this methodology aims to improve the accuracy and efficiency of 
defect detection in Betaguard sealing, finally enhancing the safety and quality declaration of 
electric vehicles. 
Fig.2 Framework for Defect Detection in Betaguard Sealing 
17 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
3.1 Data Acquisition 
1. Source of Data: 
o Data Source: Images were obtained directly from Volvo Cars' manufacturing line, 
focusing on Betaguard Yellow Sealing applied to battery lids. This confirmed the data 
was relevant to the specific defects that the model was considered to detect. 
o Collaboration: Close collaboration with Volvo’s manufacturing and quality assurance 
teams confirmed access to a complete and high-quality dataset. The team provided 
insights into common defects, which guided the data collection process. 
2. High-Resolution Image Capture: 
o Camera Setup: High-resolution cameras were strategically installed within the 
production environment to capture detailed images of the Betaguard sealing process. 
The cameras were organized to capture images at a resolution of 1920x1080 pixels, 
providing the necessary detail for identifying small and subtle defects. 
o Lighting Conditions: Multiple lighting setups were used to capture images under 
different conditions. This approach was important for creating a robust dataset that 
could generalize well across varying real-world situations. 
o Image Diversity: Images were captured from different angles and views to include a 
wide range of defect appearances. This diversity was critical for confirming that the 
model could handle various positions of defects. 
The choice of high-resolution images was determined by the need for precision in detecting 
small defects in Betaguard sealing. By capturing images under different lighting conditions and 
angles, the dataset was made more complete, enabling the model to perform reliably in diverse 
situations. 
3.2 Pre-processing 
1. Video to Frame Conversion: 
o Extraction Process: The raw video footage from the production line was methodically 
converted into individual frames using the OpenCV library. Frames were extracted at a 
rate of one frame per second to ensure a thorough and detailed dataset. 
o Frame Selection: Each frame was reviewed to select those that best represented the 
sealing process and potential defects, confirming that the dataset was focused and 
relevant. 
2. Image Cropping: 
o Defining Region of Interest (ROI): Using the cropping function in OpenCV, the 
images were cropped to focus exclusively on the Betaguard sealing area. This step was 
crucial for removing background noise and inappropriate details that could confuse the 
model. 
3. Image Resizing: 
o Standardization: Cropped images were resized to a uniform resolution of 320x320 
pixels. This resolution was chosen based on the balance between computational 
effectiveness and the retention of important features necessary for defect detection. 
18 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
4. Noise Reduction: 
o Gaussian Blur: To smooth the images, a 5x5 kernel size Gaussian blur was used. This 
step was necessary to reduce the impact of random pixel noise that could lead to false 
positives during defect detection. 
o Median Filtering: In addition to Gaussian blur, median filtering was employed to 
further reduce noise, particularly speckle noise that is common in industrial images. 
5. Image Normalization: 
o Intensity Scaling. A histogram equalization technique was used to scale the intensity 
values of each image to a range of [0, 255]. Including this normalizing step provided the 
standardization of images taken under different lighting conditions, therefore enhancing 
the reliability of the defect detection procedure. 
o Batch Normalization Preparation: Normalized images were prepared for 
subsequent batch normalization during model training, which helps stabilize and 
accelerate the training process. 
The pre-processing steps were carefully selected to enhance the quality of the images and 
decrease variability, which is critical for achieving accurate defect detection. By standardizing 
the images, the model could focus on identifying defects rather than being misled by variations 
in lighting or image noise. 
3.3 Feature Extraction 
1. Color-Based Segmentation: 
o Color Space Conversion: Images were converted from RGB to HSV(Hue Saturation 
Value) color space to control the distinct color characteristics of Betaguard Yellow 
Sealing. The HSV space allowed for more exact segmentation of the sealing area by 
dividing the hue, saturation, and value ranges specific to the seal. 
o Mask Creation: A binary mask was created by defining a specific range of HSV values 
that corresponded to the color of the Betaguard seal. This mask was applied to each 
image to separate the sealing area, ensuring that the analysis was focused only on the 
region of interest. 
2. Edge Detection: 
o Canny Edge Detection: This technique was used to identify boundaries and sharp 
transitions within the images. This method was chosen because it is quite accurate in 
identifying edges, which is important for identifying defects in the sealing material, such 
as uneven surfaces or cracks. 
o Parameter Tuning: The lower and upper thresholds of the Canny algorithm were 
precisely designed to improve edge identification without producing excessive noise or 
removing important data. 
3. Thresholding: 
o Binary Thresholding: Binary thresholding was applied to further separate the 
foreground (the Betaguard sealing) from the background. By converting the grayscale 
image to a binary image, the model could more easily identify and classify defects based 
on the intensity contrast between the seal and the nearby area. 
19 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
o Adaptive Thresholding: In cases where lighting conditions varied significantly across 
the image, adaptive thresholding was employed to adjust the threshold value locally, 
confirming consistent defect detection across the complete image. 
4. Contour Analysis: 
o Contour Extraction: Contours were extracted from the thresholded images to outline 
the shape of the sealing area. This step was crucial for identifying basic defects that clear 
as irregularities in the contour shape. 
o Shape Analysis: Each contour was analyzed based on its geometric properties, such as 
area, perimeter, and shape complexity. This analysis helped in unique between normal 
sealing and defective areas where the shape deviated from the expected pattern. 
Feature extraction techniques were selected to focus on the critical aspects of Betaguard sealing 
that are revealing of defects. By separating the sealing area through color-based segmentation 
and analyzing edges and contours, the model could accurately identify and classify defects 
based on their visual characteristics. 
Methods ignored 
Sobel edge detection was excluded from this project due to its limitations in capturing fine 
details and handling noise. While Sobel is useful for detecting basic edges, it often struggles 
with subtle defects because it only calculates gradients in two directions and can produce less 
precise edge maps. This method is also more susceptible to noise, which can lead to false or 
messy edges that complicate defect detection. For identifying small or complex defects in 
Betaguard Yellow sealing, more advanced techniques like Canny edge detection are preferred 
because they offer better precision and accuracy by employing a multi-stage process that 
includes noise reduction and detailed edge alteration. 
3.4 Model Development 
1. Selection of Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs): 
o CNNs were chosen for their powerful ability to process and analyze image data by 
automatically learning hierarchical feature representations. Their structure, which 
includes multiple layers of convolutional filters, pooling, and fully connected layers, 
makes them particularly suitable for defect detection tasks that require detailed analysis 
of image features. 
2. Implementation of VGG16 Architecture: 
o Model Architecture: The VGG16 architecture was selected due to its deep network 
structure, consisting of 16 layers including 13 convolutional layers followed by 3 fully 
connected layers. This depth allowed the model to capture both low-level and high-level 
features necessary for identifying subtle defects in Betaguard sealing. 
o Transfer Learning: Pre-trained weights from the ImageNet dataset were utilized, 
followed by fine-tuning on the Betaguard dataset. This approach leveraged the extensive 
feature learning from a large, diverse dataset while adapting the model to the specific 
task of defect detection. 
3. Training the Model: 
20 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
o Data Augmentation: Rotations, flips, zooming, and shifting were among the data 
augmentation techniques used to overcome the defect dataset's limited size. The dataset 
was dramatically increased as a result, and the model's generalization to new, untested 
data was improved. 
o Optimization: The Adam optimizer was used for its adaptive learning rate capabilities, 
which helped in efficiently minimizing the loss function. Dropout layers were 
incorporated to prevent overfitting by randomly deactivating neurons during the 
training process. 
3.5. Validation and Testing 
Test Set Evaluation: A different test set that wasn't used for training or validation was used 
to assess the model's performance. This provides a fair evaluation of the model's ability to 
identify defects in the real world. 
The VGG16 architecture and CNNs were selected due to their effectiveness in image 
classification tasks and their ability to manage complex visual data. The model was able to start 
with a solid basis due to the application of transfer learning, and it was subsequently adjusted 
to meet the particular needs of Betaguard defect detection. 
Methods Ignored  
You Only Look Once, or YOLO Model 
Although YOLO's real-time detection capabilities were taken into consideration, the project 
ultimately decided against using it because accuracy was more important than speed of 
detection. To achieve high precision in identifying minor and complicated defects, the strength 
of YOLO in fast object identification was less relevant. 
3.6 Collaboration and Feedback 
Regular discussions were held with Volvo Cars to review and validate the findings from the 
defect detection models. These meetings were crucial in ensuring that the research remained 
aligned with practical industry requirements. The feedback received helped refine the models, 
particularly in terms of focusing on the most critical defect types and adjusting the evaluation 
criteria to meet Volvo's quality standards. 
