Using an Intel Core i7 processor and 16GB of RAM, a personal computer, Python 3.8 and 
OpenCV 4.5.2 were used for the pre-processing. 
The proposed methodology is divided into several steps during the implementation phase, 
which includes data pre-processing, model development, training, and evaluation.  
Making use of Python programming language and popular libraries such as TensorFlow and 
Keras, the implementation process expedites the practical understanding of the defect 
detection system for Betaguard sealing. 
The following libraries were utilised 
OpenCV (cv2): OpenCV was used for a variety of tasks including image processing, video 
frame extraction, resizing, and cropping. It provided essential functionalities for manipulating 
and pre-processing raw image data. 
NumPy: NumPy played a major role in handling numerical computations and array 
operations. It provided efficient data structures and functions for performing mathematical 
operations on large multidimensional arrays. 
Matplotlib: Matplotlib facilitated the generation of informative visualisations for data 
exploration, model performance analysis, and result visualisation. It offered a versatile set of 
plotting functions and tools for creating publication-quality plots and figures. 
Pandas: Particularly for tabular data, pandas assisted in the manipulation and analysis of 
structured data. Along with features for data cleaning, transformation, and aggregation, it also 
offered strong data structures including Data Frames and Series. 
Scikit-learn: This package, containing a variety of machine learning algorithms, pre
processing methods, and evaluation measures, was also integrated into the model
development process. It was appropriate for research and real-world applications since it 
offered an easy-to-use interface for creating and assessing machine learning models. 
Together, these libraries made it easier to use the suggested approaches, which allowed for 
effective data processing, model development, training, and evaluation. 
4.1 Dataset  
The dataset used for training and evaluating the defect detection model consists of 1600 
images, evenly distributed across four classes. This balanced dataset helps ensure that the 
model receives an equal representation of each type of defect, which is crucial for achieving 
unbiased performance. The details of the dataset are as follows: 
No Defects: 400 images 
This class includes images where no defects are present. The absence of defects provides the 
model with a reference point understanding of normal, defect-free images. 
Crack: 400 images 
22 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
This class contains images showing various types of cracks. One of the primary defects that 
must be properly identified in order to stop material breaks is cracks. 
Uneven Seal: 400 images 
This class includes images representing uneven sealing. Detecting uneven seals is essential for 
ensuring the integrity and functionality of sealed components. 
Seal Overflow: 400 images 
Images showing seal overflow. Identifying this defect is important for maintaining quality 
control in manufacturing processes. 
Dataset Preparation 
Each image in the dataset was pre-processed using a series of steps to enhance the features 
relevant for defect detection. These pre-processing steps started from converting the images to 
HSV colour space, applying masks to filter specific colour ranges, and using edge detection and 
contour finding techniques to highlight the defect areas. 
After that, the image sets were split into training (80%) and test (20%) sets in order to 
efficiently train and evaluate the model. This section verifies that the model's performance is 
evaluated using real data, offering an accurate estimate of its capacity for generalization. 
4.2 Pre-processing 
The images used in this study are collected from an industrial setting, capturing various 
instances of seals with potential defects.  
Video to Frame Conversion: Upon completion of data acquisition, the pre-processing 
stage initiates with the conversion of captured videos into individual frames using the OpenCV 
(Open Source Computer Vision) library. Each frame is extracted at regular intervals from the 
recorded videos, ensuring comprehensive coverage of the Betaguard sealing process. By 
converting videos into frames, the data is transformed into a format conducive to subsequent 
analysis and processing. 
Image Cropping: Following frame extraction, the next step in pre-processing involves 
cropping each frame to focus solely on the Betaguard sealing area of interest. Using OpenCV's 
image manipulation functions, a region of interest (ROI) encompassing the Betaguard sealing 
is defined and extracted from each frame. By isolating the Betaguard sealing area, irrelevant 
background information is removed, optimising the dataset for subsequent defect detection 
algorithms. 
Image Resizing: The cropped Betaguard sealing images are then resized to a standardised 
resolution of 320 x 320 pixels. This resizing operation is performed using OpenCV's image 
manipulation functionalities, ensuring uniformity and consistency across the dataset. Resizing 
the images to a fixed resolution facilitates computational efficiency during subsequent analysis 
and model development while preserving essential features necessary for defect detection 
algorithms. 
