4.4.1. Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) 
Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) is chosen for this project for their better ability to learn 
hierarchical features from raw image data, making them well-suited for image classification 
tasks such as defect detection in Betaguard sealing. The CNN architecture includes multiple 
convolutional layers, each followed by a pooling layer to progressively reduce spatial 
dimensions and extract essential features. Dropout layers are incorporated to prevent over 
fitting by randomly deactivating neurons during training. Leaky ReLU activation functions are 
applied to introduce non-linearity and alleviate the vanishing gradient problem. To enable the 
model to output probability distributions over the classes, a densely connected layer with a 
softmax activation function is composed of the final layer. To improve model generalization 
and reduce overfitting one of the regularization approaches such as L2 regularization is 
applied. 
4.4.2. Visual Geometry Group (VGG)16 
VGG16, well-known for its deep architecture and remarkable performance in image 
recognition tasks, is also engaged in the project for defect detection in Betaguard sealing. A 
powerful feature extractor VGG16 is used because it has been pre-trained on the ImageNet 
dataset and is capable of capturing minute defects in images. The pre-trained VGG16 model is 
c21binba 
adjusted using fine-tuning techniques to fit to the specific defect detection task. Multiple 
convolutional layers compose the model architecture, which is then followed by max-pooling 
layers to downsample feature maps. 
Dropout layers are integrated to prevent over fitting, while Leaky ReLU activation functions 
introduce non-linearity. The final layer includes a densely connected layer with a softmax 
activation function, enabling the model to predict the probability distribution over the classes. 
4.5 Training and Optimization 
The training and optimization phase of deep learning models is vital in developing an effective 
defect detection system for Betaguard sealing. The key steps involved in this section are 
training the models and optimising their performance to achieve accurate defect detection. 
Data Augmentation and Class Weighting: To address class imbalance and improve 
model generalisation, the training dataset are expanded to apply Data augmentation 
techniques such as rotation, flipping, and zooming. Additionally, class weights are adjusted to 
ensure balanced learning, especially when dealing with unequally distributed classes. 
Hyperparameter Tuning: The performance of deep learning models are determined by 
using hyperparameters. To optimise hyperparameters such as learning rate, batch size, and the 
number of layers, techniques like grid search or random search are employed. To improve the 
model's performance and improves its ability to generalise to unseen data, optimization 
process are fine-tuned. 
Model Compilation: The model is compiled with suitable configurations, including the 
choice of loss function, optimizer, and evaluation metrics are used before training,. In this case, 
'categorical_crossentropy' is chosen as the loss function, 'adam' optimizer is used for gradient 
descent, and 'accuracy' is selected as the evaluation metric. 
Training: The fit method is used for model training, which takes the training data generator 
as input. Additionally, a validation data generator is provided to monitor the model's 
performance on unseen data during training. The EarlyStopping callback is employed to halt 
training if there is no improvement in validation loss after a certain number of epochs, 
preventing overfitting. The best weights of the model are restored using the 
restore_best_weights parameter. 
Monitoring Training Progress: The training history is stored in the history variable, 
containing metrics such as loss and accuracy for both training and validation sets across 
epochs. This information enables performance analysis and visualisation, facilitating insights 
into the model's learning process and guiding further optimization efforts. 
The training and optimization phase is essential for developing accurate deep learning models 
for defect detection in Betaguard sealing. By systematically fine-tuning hyperparameters, 
applying data augmentation techniques, and monitoring training progress, the models can be 
fine-tuned to attain optimal performance, leading to improved accuracy and reliability in 
defect detection. 
