5. Results 
5.1. Baseline Benchmark CNN model 
Method without Pre-Processing 
This section outlines the method for our baseline Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) model, 
which is considered to operate on raw, unprocessed data. This baseline setup serves as a 
reference for assessing how pre-processing techniques might affect model performance in later 
sections. 
Data Description 
The dataset used in this work consists of color images with dimensions of 320x320 pixels. 
These images are utilized without any pre-processing adjustments, such as augmentation or 
normalization. This method provides that we evaluate the model's efficiency using unmodified 
data. 
Model Architecture 
Baseline CNN model follows a straightforward architecture 
 Convolutional Layers: Three convolutional layers constitute the model's architecture. A 
max-pooling layer follows after each convolutional layer to minimize the spatial 
dimensions of the feature maps after each layer utilizes filters to extract features from the 
images. To add non-linearity, the convolutional layers use the Rectified Linear Unit 
(ReLU) activation function. 
 Dense Layers: The model switches to two fully connected (dense) layers after the 
convolutional and pooling layers. The first dense layer employs ReLU activation to further 
process the extracted features. The second dense layer, which serves as the output layer, 
uses softmax activation to classify the images into one of three categories. 
