Analysis 
 The model shows strong performance in detecting cracks and seal overflow with no 
misclassifications. 
 Since some No Defects images have been mistakenly identified as Uneven Seal, and 
vice versa, distinguishing between No Defects and Uneven Seal appears to be the 
primary challenge. The similar looks of the two classes may be the cause of these 
misclassifications, suggesting that more preprocessing or fine-tuning may be necessary 
to improve performance in these places. 
The baseline CNN model demonstrates strong performance, particularly in detecting cracks 
and seal overflow, with perfect precision and recall for these classes. However, there is some 
room for improvement in distinguishing between No Defects and Uneven Seal. Overall, with a 
test accuracy of 88.75%, the model provides a solid foundation for defect detection tasks, with 
potential for further optimization. 
Use pre-processing techniques in combination with a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to 
increase the accuracy of categorizing "No Defects" and "Uneven Seal." Pre-processing uses 
techniques including thresholding, masking, edge detection, grayscale conversion, and HSV 
conversion to improve image quality and highlight unique characteristics. By highlighting 
significant differences and extracting necessary information from background noise, these 
strategies help the model distinguish more reliably between these closely related categories 
and decrease misclassifications. 
5.2. Convolutional Neural Networks 
With Pre-processing techniques 
In this section, the implementation of pre-processing techniques applied to all images in the 
CNN model. By incorporating pre-processing across the entire dataset, aim to enhance the 
model's performance and address previous misclassification issues. 
Data Pre-processing 
1. HSV Conversion: Images have been converted into the hue, saturation, and value 
components separately using the HSV color space. The characteristics that set No Defects 
and Uneven Seal distinct but may not be visible in the RGB color space are highlighted by 
this modification. 
2. Edge Detection: To draw attention to the images' edges and structural elements, the Canny 
Edge Detection technique is used. This aids in identifying critical boundaries that can help 
differentiate between the two classes more effectively. 
3. Thresholding: Thresholding converts images into binary format based on pixel intensity, 
which isolates significant features and reduces the impact of irrelevant background 
elements. 
4. Grayscale Conversion: Images are also converted to grayscale to focus solely on brightness. 
This simplifies the data and enhances the model’s ability to detect structural differences 
between the classes. 
5. Masking: Specific regions of interest are isolated through masking, which highlights crucial 
areas for distinguishing "No Defects" from "Uneven Seal." 
35 | Defect  Detection 
