5.3. VGG 16 
VGG 16-Based Convolutional Neural Network for Image Classification 
Model Overview: Pre-trained Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) model VGG16 was the 
base for the custom image classification task and it is famous for its deep architecture. It 
consisting of 16 weight layers (13 convolutional layers and 3 fully connected layers). This model 
performs well in various computer vision tasks mainly that involve image classification tasks. 
Model Architecture: The architecture of the model is based on the standard VGG16 
architecture, which includes the following components: 
38 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
Convolutional Layers: Several convolutional layers with 3x3 filters constitute the model, 
which is stacked to extract complex information from the input images. Max-pooling layers 
(2x2) are implemented after each convolutional block to minimize the feature maps' spatial 
dimensions. 
Fully Connected Layers: The final layers of the VGG16 model include fully connected 
layers, followed by a softmax layer for classification. 
Transfer Learning 
 Transfer learning was utilized by loading pre-trained weights from VGG16 trained on 
the ImageNet dataset. 
 The top layers were modified to suit the specific classification task involving four 
classes: Crack, No Defects, Seal Overflow, and Uneven Seal. 
Output Layer: In the output layer consist of four neurons, which match the four classes in 
the dataset. To calculate the probabilities for each class a softmax activation function is used. 
Training and Optimization 
 Data Augmentation: Random rotations, flips, and shifts were useful to the training 
dataset to increase the strength of the model. 
 Optimizer: A combination of Adam optimizer and a learning rate scheduler were 
applied to dynamically correct the learning rate during training. 
 Loss Function: The loss function Categorical cross-entropy was used for the multi class 
classification tasks. 
 Metrics: To evaluate the model’s performance, Accuracy was the primary measure. 
