6. Discussion 
6.1 Theoretical Framework 
 The application of Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) in defect detection is 
grounded in established theories from machine learning and computer vision. CNNs are 
ideal for image recognition due to their ability to learn and extract hierarchical features 
from pixel data. This ability stems from deep learning principles, which enable CNNs to 
automatically identify relevant features that are critical for detecting defects in 
manufacturing processes. 
 Choice of CNNs, particularly the use of transfer learning with pre-trained models like 
VGG16, is based on the theory that pre-trained networks can significantly boost 
performance on specific tasks, especially when defect data is limited. Transfer learning 
leverages features learned from extensive datasets (such as ImageNet) and adapts them 
for defect detection in Betaguard yellow seals. This approach not only shortens the 
training time but also enhances accuracy by utilizing pre-existing patterns that are useful 
across different visual contexts. 
 Additionally, integrating batch normalization, dropout, and data augmentation 
techniques into our network architecture is informed by theoretical insights into 
regularization and model robustness. Batch normalization helps stabilize the training 
process and accelerates convergence by normalizing the layer inputs. Dropout serves as 
a regularization technique, reducing over fitting by randomly disabling neurons during 
training. Data augmentation, meanwhile, artificially expands the training dataset by 
creating variations of the original images, which helps improve the model's 
generalization capabilities. 
6.2 Methods, Implementation, and Results 
 Techniques and Model Performance: The methodologies employed aimed to enhance the 
effectiveness of CNNs in detecting defects in Betaguard yellow seals. A dataset developed 
especially for this work, which included images of seals with a variety of defects such 
cracks, seal overflow, and uneven application, was used to refine the VGG16 model, 
which is known for its deep architecture and validated performance in image 
classification. 
 Data Preparation and Augmentation: Limited number of defect data, therefore 
augmentation techniques like rotation, zooming, and horizontal flipping are applied. 
These methods increased the dataset's size and variability, making the model more 
resilient to different defect manifestations and perspectives. 
 Model Training and Optimization: For the parameter updates, the model was trained 
using categorical cross-entropy as the loss function and the Adam optimizer. To speed 
up the training process and reduce internal covariate shift Batch normalization was 
applied after each convolutional layer. Dropout layers were incorporated to mitigate over 
fitting by randomly deactivating neurons during training sessions. 
 The fine-tuned VGG16 model achieved an impressive accuracy of 93% on the test set, 
44 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
demonstrating its ability to reliably detect defects in Betaguard yellow seals. But as the 
confusion matrix showed, the model performed well in detecting some defects but poorly 
in others, particularly those with subtle or identical looks. This shows that transfer 
learning is beneficial, but it also underlines the need for a more varied dataset and 
possible architectural changes for the model. 
Several challenges were identified 
 Environmental Variability: Differences in lighting and backgrounds can affect image 
quality and detection accuracy. This can be mitigated by employing robust pre
processing techniques like normalization and noise reduction. 
 Background Noise: Unwanted objects or noise in the background can interfere with 
defect detection. Effective cropping and filtering are essential to focus on the relevant 
parts of the image. 
 Obstruction Issues: Obstacles that block the camera’s view can lead to unusable images. 
Developing algorithms to detect and exclude such images is crucial for maintaining data 
quality. 
 Lack of Defect Data: The scarcity of defective images is a significant challenge. By 
increasing the dataset and utilizing pre-trained models, data augmentation techniques 
like transfer learning help with resolving this problem. 
Comparison with Previous Studies 
 Our findings align with prior research that has utilized Convolutional Neural Networks 
(CNNs) for defect detection. Particularly, Chen et al. (2021) conducted a study on surface 
defect detection using deep learning techniques [8]. Their work highlighted similar 
challenges in distinguishing subtle defects, particularly when using CNN-based 
architectures. They achieved comparable accuracy levels but emphasized the necessity of 
more diverse datasets to improve the model's ability to identify visually similar defects. 
 In contrast, Lakshmanna et al. (2022) explored the use of the VGG16 model for detecting 
defects in circuit manufacturing [15]. Their study reported slightly lower accuracy than 
ours, which they attributed to a less diverse dataset and the absence of advanced 
augmentation techniques. In our research, we implemented extensive data 
augmentation methods, such as rotation, zooming, and horizontal flipping. These 
techniques increased the size and variability of our dataset, making the model more 
resilient to different defect manifestations and perspectives. This broader approach to 
data augmentation likely accounts for the higher accuracy observed in our study, 
underscoring the importance of dataset variability in enhancing CNN performance. 
 Additionally, our implementation of transfer learning has shown a significant boost in 
performance compared to studies that trained models from scratch. Miller et al. (2020) 
discussed how models trained from scratch on limited datasets often underperform 
compared to those utilizing transfer learning [16]. Their findings support our approach, 
which leverages pre-trained networks to enhance performance, particularly when defect 
data is limited. 
45 | Defect  Detection 
c21binba 
 Our optimization strategies, including the use of categorical cross-entropy as the loss 
function, the Adam optimizer for parameter updates, batch normalization, and dropout, 
were also validated by similar studies. For example, Krizhevsky et al. (2017) 
demonstrated the effectiveness of batch normalization and dropout in improving the 
stability and accuracy of CNN models [20]. Our results are consistent with these findings, 
showing that such optimization techniques are crucial for achieving high performance in 
defect detection tasks. 
 Overall, our research builds on and extends the findings of these previous studies, 
demonstrating the importance of diverse datasets, advanced augmentation techniques, 
and transfer learning in achieving superior defect detection performance. 
6.3. Ethical and Societal Implications 
6.3.1 Ethical Considerations 
Ethical considerations were carefully followed throughout this research to ensure that all 
standards were met and that the rights and privacy of everyone involved were respected. Key 
points include: 
 Data Privacy and Consent: All images used were provided by Volvo Cars with full 
consent. The data was handled responsibly, with sensitive information being 
anonymised where necessary to protect identities and confidential processes. 
 Bias Mitigation: The dataset was created to represent all defect types fairly, 
preventing the model from favouring any specific class. This helps ensure that the 
defect detection works fairly across all categories. 
 Transparency: The research is documented openly, detailing data sources, pre
processing steps, and model configurations. This transparency makes it easier for 
others to understand, reproduce, and evaluate the work. 
 Impact on Employment: The introduction of automated systems has potential 
effects on jobs. The research acknowledges this and suggests ways to use technology to 
complement, not replace, human workers, supporting a balanced integration into 
manufacturing. 
 Environmental Responsibility: The research aims to reduce defects, which in turn 
helps minimize waste and improve the use of resources. This contributes to 
environmental sustainability goals. 
6.3.2 Societal Implications 
 Product Quality and Safety: Implementing advanced defect detection systems, 
especially in the battery lid sealing process at Volvo Cars, is crucial for improving 
product quality and safety. By catching defects early, the project helps ensure that 
electric vehicle batteries are safer and more reliable, benefiting both consumers and 
Volvo Cars' reputation. 
 Environmental Impact: Using automated defect detection reduces waste and saves 
46 | Defect  Detection 
